{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The first category is nondispositive motions, which include motions for other parties (not named in the case) to intervene, motions to amend pleadings, and motions for attorneys to be admitted pro hac vice (meaning they wish to appear before a court in which they are not already formally admitted to practice) (Practical Law Litigation 2023e).",
    "Discovery motions, which deal with evidence, are also filed.",
    "These include, for example, motions to compel discovery, quash or modify a subpoena, sanction parties for failure to preserve evidence, and other motions (Practical Law Litigation 2023b).",
    "Dispositive motions are also common, such as a motion for summary judgment, a MTD (if not already filed and decided), or a motion for default judgment (Practical Law Litigation 2023c).",
    "Finally, attorneys may file evidentiary pre-trial motions, such as motions in limine, which concern evidence to be presented to the jury, and Daubert motions which relate to expert testimony (Weinberger et al. 2023)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Finally, attorneys may file evidentiary pre-trial motions, such as motions in limine, which concern evidence to be presented to the jury, and Daubert motions which relate to expert testimony (Weinberger et al. 2023)."
  ]
}